{"output": "# Solr to OpenSearch Migration Report — `ecommerce`

## Step 1 — Schema Conversion

Here is the equivalent OpenSearch index mapping:

```json
{
  "settings": {
    "analysis": {
      "analyzer": {
        "text_general_index": {
          "type": "custom",
          "tokenizer": "standard",
          "filter": ["lowercase"]
        }
      }
    }
  },
  "mappings": {
    "properties": {
      "id": { "type": "keyword" },
      "title": {
        "type": "text",
        "analyzer": "text_general_index",
        "copy_to": "title_sort",
        "fields": {
          "keyword": { "type": "keyword" }
        }
      },
      "title_sort": { "type": "keyword" },
      "price": { "type": "integer" },
      "location": { "type": "geo_point" },
      "created_at": { "type": "date" }
    }
  }
}
```

**Field-by-field notes:**

| Solr Field | Solr Type | OpenSearch Type | Notes |
|---|---|---|---|
| `id` | `solr.StrField` | `keyword` | Pass as document `_id` at index time and keep as a field for queries. |
| `title` | `solr.TextField` (standard + lowercase) | `text` with custom analyzer | Added `.keyword` sub-field for exact match/aggregation use. |
| `title_sort` | (copyField target) | `keyword` | Receives `copy_to` from `title`. Needed for sorting on the title field. |
| `price` | `solr.IntPointField` | `integer` | `doc_values: true` is the OpenSearch default — no action needed. |
| `location` | `solr.LatLonPointSpatialField` | `geo_point` | **Coordinate order differs** — see incompatibilities. |
| `created_at` | `solr.DatePointField` | `date` | ISO 8601 format. |

---

## Step 2 — Incompatibility Analysis

### Breaking

| # | Category | Description | Recommendation |
|---|---|---|---|
| 1 | Schema | **`copyField` to `copy_to`** — Solr `<copyField source="title" dest="title_sort"/>` has no wildcard issue here, but `title_sort` is not explicitly typed in the Solr schema. If it was intended as a `string` for sorting, it must be declared as `keyword` in OpenSearch. | Declare `title_sort` as `keyword` in the mapping (done above). Verify the Solr `title_sort` fieldType — if it was `text_general`, sorting would be tokenized and broken in both systems. |
| 2 | Query | **Spatial coordinate order** — Solr `LatLonPointSpatialField` uses `lat,lon`. OpenSearch `geo_point` accepts `{"lat": x, "lon": y}` (object) or `[lon, lat]` (GeoJSON array). If your data uses `"lat,lon"` strings, OpenSearch also accepts that format, but GeoJSON array order is reversed. | Audit indexed geo data format. If using arrays, swap to `[lon, lat]`. Safest: use object form `{"lat": x, "lon": y}`. |

### Behavioral

| # | Category | Description | Recommendation |
|---|---|---|---|
| 3 | Query | **Relevance scoring: TF-IDF vs BM25** — Solr defaults to TF-IDF (ClassicSimilarity); OpenSearch defaults to BM25. BM25 saturates term frequency, so documents with high term repetition score lower. Expect different top-10 ordering. | Run shadow queries comparing top-10 overlap for 2–4 weeks before cutover. Tune BM25 `k1`/`b` per field if needed. See Relevance Tuning section below. |
| 4 | Schema | **Asymmetric analyzer** — Your Solr schema defines only an `index` analyzer on `text_general` with no explicit `query` analyzer. Solr falls back to the index analyzer for queries. OpenSearch behaves the same way (single `analyzer` is used for both), so this is functionally equivalent. However, if you later need a separate search analyzer (e.g., to skip stemming at query time), add `search_analyzer` explicitly. | No action required now. Note for future tuning. |
| 5 | Schema | **`stored="true"` vs `_source`** — Solr stores fields individually; OpenSearch returns the full `_source` document. All your fields are `stored="true"`, so behavior is equivalent. If you rely on partial stored fields elsewhere, use `_source` filtering. | No action required for this schema. |
| 6 | Feature | **Commit/refresh semantics** — Solr soft commit ≈ OpenSearch refresh. Default `refresh_interval` is `1s`, so documents are near-real-time but not instantly searchable. | Set `refresh_interval` based on your freshness requirements. During bulk migration, set to `"-1"` and restore after. |

### Summary: 2 Breaking, 4 Behavioral, 0 Unsupported.

---

## Step 3 — Query Translation

### Query: `title:opensearch AND price:[10 TO 100]`

**Solr (standard parser):**
```
q=title:opensearch AND price:[10 TO 100]
```

**OpenSearch Query DSL:**
```json
{
  "query": {
    "bool": {
      "must": [
        { "match": { "title": "opensearch" } },
        { "range": { "price": { "gte": 10, "lte": 100 } } }
      ]
    }
  }
}
```

**Translation notes:**

- `title:opensearch` → `match` query (analyzed, single term). If exact match is intended, use `term` on `title.keyword` instead.
- `price:[10 TO 100]` → `range` with `gte`/`lte` (square brackets = inclusive in both Solr and OpenSearch).
- The `price` range filter does not affect scoring. If you want it as a non-scoring filter (recommended for performance), move it to `bool.filter`:

```json
{
  "query": {
    "bool": {
      "must": [
        { "match": { "title": "opensearch" } }
      ],
      "filter": [
        { "range": { "price": { "gte": 10, "lte": 100 } } }
      ]
    }
  }
}
```

This preserves Solr `fq` semantics (non-scoring, cacheable) and is the recommended pattern.

**No query-level incompatibilities found** for this specific query. It translates cleanly.

---

## Step 4 — Customizations

No custom request handlers, plugins, or auth mechanisms were provided. If you have any `solrconfig.xml` customizations (UpdateRequestProcessorChains, custom SearchComponents, auth), surface them before cutover.

---

## Step 5 — Client Migration: SolrJ → opensearch-java

**Dependency change:**

Replace `org.apache.solr:solr-solrj` with:
```xml
<!-- Maven -->
<dependency>
  <groupId>org.opensearch.client</groupId>
  <artifactId>opensearch-java</artifactId>
  <version>2.18.0</version>
</dependency>
```

**Client init — before (SolrJ):**
```java
SolrClient solrClient = new HttpSolrClient.Builder("http://localhost:8983/solr/ecommerce").build();
```

**Client init — after (opensearch-java):**
```java
RestClientTransport transport = new RestClientTransport(
    RestClient.builder(new HttpHost("localhost", 9200)).build(),
    new JacksonJsonpMapper()
);
OpenSearchClient client = new OpenSearchClient(transport);
```

**Query — before (SolrJ):**
```java
SolrQuery query = new SolrQuery("title:opensearch AND price:[10 TO 100]");
QueryResponse response = solrClient.query(query);
```

**Query — after (opensearch-java):**
```java
SearchResponse<Product> response = client.search(s -> s
    .index("ecommerce")
    .query(q -> q.bool(b -> b
        .must(m -> m.match(mp -> mp.field("title").query("opensearch")))
        .filter(f -> f.range(r -> r.field("price").gte(JsonData.of(10)).lte(JsonData.of(100))))
    )),
    Product.class
);
```

**Key differences:**
- SolrJ uses Solr query strings; opensearch-java uses type-safe DSL builders. Full rewrite required.
- No ZooKeeper dependency — point the client at the cluster load balancer.
- Configure `maxConnPerRoute` and `maxConnTotal` explicitly to match your concurrency level.
- Auth: if migrating from Solr Basic Auth, pass credentials via `RestClient.builder(...).setHttpClientConfigCallback(...)`.

---

## Step 6 — Cluster Sizing

You haven't provided cluster topology details. To give precise recommendations, I need:

- Standalone Solr or SolrCloud? Number of nodes, shards, replicas?
- Approximate document count and total index size?
- Peak query throughput (QPS) and indexing rate (docs/sec)?

**General guidance based on this schema** (small e-commerce catalog):

| Parameter | Recommendation |
|---|---|
| Shards | Start with 1 primary shard if data < 25 GB; scale to `ceil(data_GB * 1.5 / 25)` |
| Replicas | 1 (production); 0 during bulk migration |
| Dedicated masters | 3 (m5.large or equivalent) for any production cluster |
| Data node heap | 50% of RAM, max 32 GB. Match or exceed your Solr heap. |
| AZ distribution | 3 AZs minimum |

---

## Step 7 — Migration Report

### Executive Summary

A small, clean e-commerce schema with standard field types and one `copyField`. Migration complexity is **low**. Two breaking issues require attention before cutover (coordinate order for geo data, `title_sort` field declaration). Scoring differences (TF-IDF → BM25) are the primary relevance risk.

### Incompatibility Summary

| Severity | Count | Items |
|---|---|---|
| Breaking | 2 | `copyField`/`title_sort` type declaration; geo coordinate order |
| Behavioral | 4 | BM25 scoring; asymmetric analyzer (no action needed); `_source` semantics; refresh timing |
| Unsupported | 0 | — |

### Blockers

1. **Geo coordinate order** — Must audit all indexed location data and client code that constructs geo queries. Incorrect order silently returns wrong results.
2. **`title_sort` field type** — Confirm the Solr fieldType for this field. If it's not `string`/`StrField`, the `keyword` mapping above needs adjustment.

### Stage Plan

| Phase | Duration | Activities |
|---|---|---|
| **1. Prepare** | Week 1–2 | Create OpenSearch index with mapping above. Deploy synonym/stopword files if any. Set up monitoring (cluster health, slow logs). |
| **2. Bulk Load** | Week 2–3 | `refresh_interval: -1`, `replicas: 0`. Bulk index from Solr export (5–15 MB batches, 2–4 concurrent streams per data node). Validate document count match. |
| **3. Post-Load** | Week 3 | Restore `refresh_interval: 1s`, `replicas: 1`. Run `_forcemerge?max_num_segments=1`. |
| **4. Relevance Baseline** | Week 3–4 | Run top 100–200 production queries against both Solr and OpenSearch. Measure nDCG@10 overlap. Tune BM25 `k1`/`b` if delta > 2%. |
| **5. Client Migration** | Week 4–5 | Swap SolrJ → opensearch-java. Update query construction, response parsing, auth. |
| **6. Shadow Traffic** | Week 5–6 | Dual-write or replay production queries to OpenSearch. Compare latency p50/p95/p99 and result consistency. |
| **7. Cutover** | Week 7 | Canary at 1% → 10% → 50% → 100%. Keep Solr running for instant rollback for 1 week. |
| **8. Decommission** | Week 8+ | Decommission Solr + ZooKeeper after rollback window expires. |

### Relevance Tuning Recommendation

Since you're a Search Engineer, I'd recommend setting up **Quepid** against both Solr and OpenSearch endpoints during Phase 4. Create a judgment set from your top queries with a 4-point relevance scale (Perfect/Good/Fair/Bad). Use nDCG@10 as your primary metric. If BM25 defaults produce > 2% degradation, tune per-field:

```json
{
  "settings": {
    "index": {
      "similarity": {
        "title_bm25": { "type": "BM25", "k1": 0.8, "b": 0.5 }
      }
    }
  },
  "mappings": {
    "properties": {
      "title": { "type": "text", "similarity": "title_bm25" }
    }
  }
}
```

Lower `k1` (0.8) for the short `title` field reduces term frequency saturation. Lower `b` (0.5) reduces length normalization penalty since product titles are relatively uniform in length.

---

Want me to drill into any section — cluster sizing once you have topology details, additional query translations, or the geo data migration specifics?"}
